  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why hollow shaft can transmit more torque than solid shaft?",
  "response": "A hollow shaft can transmit more torque than a solid shaft of the same material and outer diameter due to the distribution of material farther away from the center. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Polar Moment of Inertia (J):**\n   The ability of a shaft to resist torsion (twisting) is determined by its polar moment of inertia (J). The polar moment of inertia for a circular shaft is given by:\n   - For a solid shaft: \\( J = \\frac{\\pi D^4}{32} \\)\n   - For a hollow shaft: \\( J = \\frac{\\pi (D_o^4 - D_i^4)}{32} \\)\n   \n   Where \\( D \\) is the diameter of the solid shaft, \\( D_o \\) is the outer diameter of the hollow shaft, and \\( D_i \\) is the inner diameter of the hollow shaft.\n\n2. **Torque Transmission:**\n   The torque (T) that a shaft can transmit is related to its polar moment of inertia by the formula:\n   \\[\n   T = \\frac{J \\tau}{r}\n   \\]\n   Where \\( \\tau \\) is the maximum shear stress, and \\( r \\) is the radius at which the stress is calculated (usually the outer radius).\n\n3. **Material Distribution:**\n   For a hollow shaft, more material is located farther from the center compared to a solid shaft of the same outer diameter. This distribution of material increases the polar moment of inertia significantly because the moment of inertia is proportional to the fourth power of the radius (\\( r^4 \\)).\n\n4. **Comparison Example:**\n   Consider a solid shaft and a hollow shaft with the same outer diameter \\( D \\). If the hollow shaft has an inner diameter \\( D_i \\) that is not too large, the polar moment of inertia of the hollow shaft will be greater than that of the solid shaft. This is because:\n   \\[\n   J_{\\text{hollow}} = \\frac{\\pi (D^4 - D_i^4)}{32} \\quad \\text{and} \\quad J_{\\text{solid}} = \\frac{\\pi D^4}{32}\n   \\]\n   As long as \\( D_i \\) is less than \\( D \\), \\( D^4 - D_i^4 \\) will be greater than \\( D^4 \\) for the same \\( D \\).\n\n5. **Weight and Material Efficiency:**\n   Additionally, a hollow shaft can be lighter than a solid shaft while still maintaining a higher torque capacity. This is advantageous in applications where weight is a critical factor.\n\nIn summary, a hollow shaft can transmit more torque than a solid shaft of the same outer diameter and material because the hollow configuration more effectively utilizes the material by placing it farther from the center, thus increasing the polar moment of inertia.",
